(a) The density matrix is
\[
\rho = p_{1,\uparrow} \frac{1}{2} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 1 & 1 \end{pmatrix} 
+ p_{1,\downarrow} \frac{1}{2} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & -1 \\ -1 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
+ p_{2,\uparrow} \frac{1}{2} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & -i \\ i & 1 \end{pmatrix}
+ p_{2,\downarrow} \frac{1}{2} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & i \\ -i & 1 \end{pmatrix}
+ p_{3,\uparrow} \frac{1}{2} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix}
+ p_{3,\downarrow} \frac{1}{2} \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}
\]
\[
= \frac{1}{2} \left( (d_1 + d_2 + d_3) + \delta_3 \quad \delta_1 - i\delta_2 \quad \delta_1 + i\delta_2 \quad (d_1 + d_2 + d_3) - \delta_3 \right)
\]
\[
= \frac{1}{2} \begin{pmatrix} 1 + \delta_3 & \delta_1 - i\delta_2 \\ \delta_1 + i\delta_2 & 1 - \delta_3 \end{pmatrix} \quad (3)
\]

(b) By inspection,
\[ a = \frac{1}{2} \quad b = \frac{1}{2} \vec{\delta} \quad (4) \]

(c) This is the same as the density matrix produced by the second electron gun if \( \hat{n} \) is parallel to \( \vec{\delta} \), and \( D = |\vec{\delta}| \).
A simple way to see this is to go to a rotated coordinate system with \( z' \) axis along \( \vec{\delta} \).

